Note:
OpenBSD ARM64 System Call Interface

This file implements OpenBSD ARM64 (AArch64) system calls.

Platform-specific details:
- Platform: OpenBSD ARM64
- Syscall mechanism: SVC instruction (svc #0)
- Syscall number register: X8
- Argument registers: X0-X5 (up to 6 arguments)
- Return value: X0 (positive on success, negative errno on error)

OpenBSD syscall convention (ARM64):
- X8 = syscall number
- X0-X5 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+ (if needed)
- X0 = return value (or -errno on error)
- Carry flag in CPSR indicates error (but typically check for negative return)

OpenBSD syscall numbers differ from Linux, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and Darwin.
This file provides both syscall number constants and wrapper functions.

Dependencies: None (uses inline assembly for syscalls)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SYSCALL NUMBER CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: OpenBSD syscall numbers (from sys/kern/syscalls.master)
Note: These are specific to OpenBSD and differ from other BSDs and Linux

Process called "openbsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
OpenBSD (like all BSDs and Darwin) does not provide a distinct `exit_group(2)`
syscall. The Linux distinction between `exit` (single thread via `do_exit`)
and `exit_group` (all threads in the thread group via `do_group_exit`) does
not apply to OpenBSD's process model: OpenBSD's kernel `sys_exit` performs
whole-process teardown, sending SIGKILL to every thread in the process via
`exit1()` in `sys/kern/kern_exit.c`. We therefore alias SYS_EXIT_GROUP to
syscall 1 (the same as SYS_EXIT) so cross-platform callers obtain the
"terminate all threads" semantic without conditional code. The arm64 svc
trap with X8=1 invokes `sys_exit`, which is what we want.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (no SYS_exit_group entry);
OpenBSD `sys/kern/kern_exit.c` sys_exit() / exit1().
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning the integer 1. Compiles to a constant-load in
the syscall_1 wrapper's stack frame, then svc #0 with X8=1 and X0=status.
The kernel's syscall table entry for index 1 dispatches to `sys_exit`,
which calls `exit1(p, status, EXIT_NORMAL)` and never returns. Identical
to SYS_EXIT() at the assembly level; the separate name exists to satisfy
the cross-platform 66-proc dispatcher surface required by P2-B.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant accessor; compiler-inlinable. The associated syscall is itself
a non-returning trap, so there is no return-path cost. The alias to
SYS_EXIT incurs zero overhead versus calling SYS_EXIT directly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Triggers whole-process termination on the kernel side. Caller-supplied
`status` is recorded in the wait-status word for the parent process and
is observable via wait4/waitpid. There is no privilege escalation path
through this syscall — the kernel only terminates the caller's own
process. Pledged processes (`pledge("stdio")` and stricter) retain the
ability to call exit; pledge restrictions do not bar self-termination.
@End Security_Scope
