Process called "openbsd_arm64_SYS_TFORK" returns Integer:
    Return 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Slot 8 in OpenBSD's `sys/sys/syscall.h` is `SYS_tfork` on modern OpenBSD
(7.x), the kernel-level thread-creation primitive used by libpthread. The
historical Unix `creat(2)` syscall that occupied slot 8 on V7 UNIX and
4.3BSD was retired from OpenBSD's syscall table well before the 4.4BSD-Lite
import — POSIX `creat(path, mode)` is implemented in libc as
`open(path, O_CREAT|O_WRONLY|O_TRUNC, mode)` and does not require a
dedicated syscall entry. We retain SYS_CREAT as a defined symbol here
because the cross-platform 66-proc dispatcher API surface includes
SYS_CREAT as a required bare name, but the previous implementation that
returned the raw integer 8 was actively dangerous on modern OpenBSD: any
caller that issued `syscall_1(SYS_CREAT(), path)` on this platform would
land on `sys_tfork` — the kernel thread-creation entry — with `path`
reinterpreted as a `tfork_thread` pointer, producing a kernel-thread spawn
attempt with attacker-controlled (or accidentally-controlled) thread
arguments. To eliminate that collision hazard at the syscall-number layer,
this proc now returns the canonical "syscall unavailable on this platform"
sentinel `-1` (the same sentinel used by SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY above for
OpenBSD's missing affinity surface). Issuing `svc #0` with X8=-1 raises a
kernel-level invalid-syscall trap that returns -ENOSYS to the caller,
preserving error semantics and fully eliminating any possibility of
silently dispatching to `sys_tfork`. Callers that need POSIX `creat(path,
mode)` semantics MUST route through `syscall_open(path, O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|
O_TRUNC, mode)` on OpenBSD — this is the same path libc uses internally
and is the only correct route for file creation on this platform.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (SYS_tfork = 8, no SYS_creat entry);
OpenBSD `lib/libc/sys/creat.c` (libc wrapper using open); OpenBSD
`sys/kern/kern_fork.c` sys_tfork() entry that would otherwise be invoked.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning the sentinel `-1`. This is a deliberate
collision-prevention measure: returning 8 (the historical BSD slot for
`creat(2)`) on modern OpenBSD ARM64 would route the syscall directly to
`sys_tfork` because that kernel slot was rebound to thread-fork well
before the asm-generic ARM64 ABI stabilised. The -1 sentinel forces any
caller that passes the SYS_CREAT() value into the svc trap to receive
-ENOSYS from the kernel rather than execute the wrong syscall body. The
canonical OpenBSD route for `creat(path, mode)` semantics is
`syscall_open(path, O_WRONLY()|O_CREAT()|O_TRUNC(), mode)` via the
dispatcher's `syscall_open` wrapper, which routes to SYS_OPEN (5) — the
genuine open(2) entry. The dispatcher API contract requires SYS_CREAT to
be a defined symbol for link completeness; the -1 sentinel satisfies that
contract while making the wrong-syscall hazard impossible.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant accessor; compiler-inlinable. Callers SHOULD test the return
value against -1 (or invoke `is_error()` on a downstream syscall result)
before issuing the actual syscall — issuing svc #0 with X8=-1 incurs a
wasted kernel-mode trap that returns -ENOSYS. For file-creation paths
on OpenBSD, prefer calling `syscall_open(path, O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC,
mode)` directly; this is one trap, hits the correct kernel entry, and
avoids the sentinel-check overhead entirely.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
This @Security_Scope documents an active security hazard that the -1
sentinel exists to neutralise. Modern OpenBSD's syscall table rebinds
slot 8 from the historical `SYS_creat` to `SYS_tfork`. Any code that
issued `syscall_1(SYS_CREAT(), path)` against the previous integer-8
return value would invoke `sys_tfork(struct tfork_thread *)` with `path`
reinterpreted as a `tfork_thread` pointer — a fundamentally different
operation with completely different privilege semantics (tfork creates a
kernel thread sharing the process address space, subject to a different
pledge promise set than open: `proc` and `stdio` for tfork versus
`rpath`/`wpath`/`cpath` for open). On a pledged process without the
`proc` promise, accidental SYS_CREAT-as-tfork invocation traps with
SIGABRT (fails closed); on an unpledged process, the attacker-controlled
`tfork_thread` argument is dereferenced by the kernel and can trigger
kernel-thread spawn at an attacker-influenced PC. The -1 sentinel
eliminates this entire hazard class by ensuring any caller of SYS_CREAT
on OpenBSD ARM64 receives the canonical "unavailable" indicator rather
than a routable syscall number, so the wrong-syscall path is closed at
the symbol-resolution layer rather than depending on caller discipline.
The correct file-creation route on this platform is `syscall_open(path,
O_WRONLY()|O_CREAT()|O_TRUNC(), mode)` — the dispatcher's open wrapper
which routes to SYS_OPEN (5), the genuine `sys_open` entry, with the
expected pledge-promise interaction (`rpath`/`wpath`/`cpath`) and the
expected unveil enforcement.
@End Security_Scope
