Process called "openbsd_arm64_SYS_OBREAK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

@Reasoning
SYS_BRK is the cross-platform 66-proc API surface name for the program-break
heap-growth syscall. OpenBSD's `sys/sys/syscall.h` names this entry
`SYS_obreak` (the historical 4.3BSD "old break" name retained for ABI
stability), and assigns it syscall number 17. SYS_BRK is provided here as
a documented alias returning the same integer 17, so dispatcher-routed
callers can use the platform-neutral name. The arm64 svc trap with X8=17
invokes `sys_obreak`, which adjusts the process's heap break to the
address supplied in X0; the kernel returns 0 on success or -ENOMEM/-EINVAL
on failure (caller checks sign of return). Modern OpenBSD libc / malloc
implementations do NOT use obreak — they use `mmap(MAP_ANON|MAP_PRIVATE)`
for heap allocation, and the obreak path is preserved only for static
binaries and legacy compatibility. Callers SHOULD prefer `syscall_mmap`
for new heap-style allocation.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (SYS_obreak = 17); OpenBSD
`sys/uvm/uvm_mmap.c` sys_obreak(); OpenBSD `lib/libc/stdlib/malloc.c`
(uses mmap, not obreak).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning the integer 17. Aliases SYS_OBREAK at the
syscall-number level — both procs return the same constant. The naming
duality reflects the cross-platform dispatcher's expectation of `SYS_BRK`
(POSIX/Linux name) and OpenBSD's native preference for `SYS_OBREAK`
(historical 4.3BSD name). Compiles to a constant-load identical to
SYS_OBREAK; the two accessors emit indistinguishable instructions.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant accessor; compiler-inlinable. The associated syscall path
(`sys_obreak`) is rarely hit on modern OpenBSD because malloc uses mmap.
For new code, prefer `syscall_mmap(0, len, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
MAP_ANON|MAP_PRIVATE, -1, 0)` over `syscall_brk` — mmap is the OpenBSD
kernel's preferred heap-growth path and aligns better with W^X policy.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The obreak syscall adjusts only the calling process's own heap break;
no cross-process memory state is touched. The kernel enforces resource
limits via `RLIMIT_DATA` (heap size cap) and aborts the syscall with
-ENOMEM if the requested break exceeds the limit. Pledged processes
retain obreak access under the `stdio` promise — sandboxed callers can
allocate heap memory without escalating pledge state. There is no
exploitable interaction with W^X: obreak'd memory is data-only (no
PROT_EXEC), so attacker-controlled writes cannot become executable
without an explicit mprotect.
@End Security_Scope
