@Reasoning
OpenBSD does not expose a `sched_getaffinity(2)` syscall. The Linux
interface (syscall 204 on x86_64, 123 on arm64 asm-generic) returns the
CPU affinity bitmask for a thread or process; OpenBSD's scheduler model
intentionally rejects user-space CPU pinning to preserve scheduler
flexibility and security. The closest available query is the sysctl
bridge `KERN_NCPUONLINE` / `KERN_NCPU` (sysctl mib { CTL_KERN,
KERN_NCPUONLINE }) which returns the count of active CPUs but does not
expose per-thread affinity state. Returning -1 here is the canonical
"no native syscall" sentinel; the dispatcher's high-level affinity
wrapper (when added) MUST route through `syscall_2(SYS_SYSCTL(), ...)`
with the appropriate mib structure to obtain the CPU count and return
a synthesised bitmask covering all available CPUs (which is the only
information OpenBSD allows user space to learn). We deliberately do
NOT alias to SYS_SYSCTL=202 directly because the calling conventions
differ entirely — `sched_getaffinity(pid, cpusetsize, mask)` versus
`sysctl(name, namelen, oldp, oldlenp, newp, newlen)` — silent
substitution corrupts callers, so the dispatcher refuses the alias.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (no SYS_sched_getaffinity entry);
OpenBSD `sys/sys/sysctl.h` (KERN_NCPUONLINE = 25); man 2 sysctl
(OpenBSD); design doc `docs/dev/designs/P2-B-cross-platform-threading
-syscalls-design.md` line 230 ("(no native — return cpu count)").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning -1. The -1 value is the canonical "syscall
unavailable on this platform" sentinel adopted by the cross-platform
syscall dispatcher; calling `syscall_3(SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY(), ...)`
on OpenBSD ARM64 with X8=-1 raises a kernel-level invalid-syscall
trap that returns -ENOSYS to the caller, preserving error semantics.
The dispatcher API contract requires SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY to be a
defined symbol for link completeness; the -1 sentinel signals "must
use the sysctl-bridge path instead."
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant accessor; compiler-inlinable. Callers SHOULD test the return
value against -1 (or invoke `is_error()` on a downstream syscall
result) before issuing the actual syscall — issuing svc #0 with X8=-1
incurs a wasted kernel-mode trap. For affinity-style queries on
OpenBSD, prefer `syscall_sysctl_ncpuonline()` (a future helper, not
yet exposed) or invoke the sysctl path directly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning -1 has no security implications on its own. The downstream
path through sysctl(2) with KERN_NCPUONLINE is unprivileged and
available under all pledge promises including `stdio`. There is no
mechanism on OpenBSD by which user code can pin a thread to a CPU,
so the absence of sched_getaffinity also eliminates the side-channel
class enabled by CPU pinning on Linux (e.g. last-level cache locality
attacks). This is a defensive default; callers requiring CPU-pinning
behaviour for correctness (not optimisation) must redesign for
OpenBSD's scheduler-managed model.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "openbsd_arm64_SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return -1
End Process



