@Reasoning
MAP_ANONYMOUS is the cross-platform 66-proc API surface name for the
mmap flag that requests anonymous (non-file-backed) memory. OpenBSD's
`sys/sys/mman.h` defines this flag as `MAP_ANON` with value 0x1000
(4096 decimal); the `MAP_ANONYMOUS` spelling is a Linux/glibc synonym
that OpenBSD does not natively declare. We provide it here as a
documented alias returning 4096 so cross-platform callers can use the
POSIX-y name without conditional compilation. The numerical value 0x1000
matches Darwin, FreeBSD, and NetBSD (all BSDs share this MAP_ANON
encoding); Linux uses 0x20 (32 decimal) instead, which is one of the
multi-platform incompatibilities the dispatcher's bare-name resolution
hides from callers.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/mman.h` (#define MAP_ANON 0x1000); design doc
`docs/dev/designs/P2-B-cross-platform-threading-syscalls-design.md`
section "Constants per platform" line 241 (NetBSD/OpenBSD MAP_ANON=
0x1000).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning the integer 4096 (= 0x1000). Aliases MAP_ANON
at the value level — both procs return the same constant. The naming
duality reflects the dispatcher's expectation of `MAP_ANONYMOUS` (Linux/
POSIX-extended name) and OpenBSD's native preference for `MAP_ANON`
(traditional BSD short name). Compiles to a constant-load identical to
MAP_ANON; the two accessors emit indistinguishable instructions.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant accessor; compiler-inlinable. Pass to `syscall_mmap` as part
of the `flags` bitmask: `MAP_ANONYMOUS() OR MAP_PRIVATE()` requests
anonymous private memory (the standard "give me clean zeroed pages"
pattern). Combining with `MAP_FIXED` requires the addr argument to be
page-aligned; OpenBSD's mmap will fail with EINVAL otherwise.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Anonymous mappings are zero-filled on allocation by the OpenBSD kernel
(per the W^X-safe heap-init policy); callers do NOT need to explicitly
zero the returned region. MAP_ANONYMOUS regions are NOT inherited
across `execve` (the kernel clears the address space). When combined
with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE|MAP_PRIVATE, this is the canonical pattern
for heap-style allocation. Combining with PROT_EXEC violates OpenBSD's
W^X policy and will be rejected by the kernel for non-static binaries;
callers requiring executable memory must mmap as PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE
first, then mprotect-up to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC after content is written.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "openbsd_arm64_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 4096
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
POSIX file mode constants for `creat`, `open(O_CREAT)`, `mkdir`, and
`chmod`. MODE_0644 (rw-r--r--) is the canonical default for regular
files; MODE_0755 (rwxr-xr-x) is the canonical default for executables
and directories. The numeric values 420 and 493 are the decimal
encodings of octal 0644 and 0755 respectively, computed as
(6 * 64) + (4 * 8) + 4 = 420 and (7 * 64) + (5 * 8) + 5 = 493. These
encodings are identical across OpenBSD, all other BSDs, Linux, and
Darwin because they predate any platform-specific divergence — they
are part of the original V7 UNIX permission model preserved by every
POSIX kernel.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/stat.h` (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200,
S_IRGRP=0040, S_IROTH=0004 = 0644; S_IRUSR|S_IWUSR|S_IXUSR|S_IRGRP|
S_IXGRP|S_IROTH|S_IXOTH = 0755); POSIX.1-2017 §sys/stat.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to this proc on
openbsd_arm64 targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.
Wave 2 will rename to `openbsd_arm64_MODE_0644`; Wave 1 keeps the bare
form to match the still-bare dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlinable. The values are passed as the
`mode` argument to file-creation syscalls — a single integer push to
X2 in the arm64 calling convention. No runtime cost beyond the
constant-load.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file-permission constant carries no security state on its
own. Callers who pass these values as the `mode` argument to `creat`/
`open(O_CREAT)`/`mkdir`/`chmod` are responsible for matching the
requested permission to the intended access policy. World-readable
(0644) is appropriate for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-
executable (0755) is appropriate for binaries and directories. Setuid
(04000), setgid (02000), and sticky (01000) bits are NOT included
here — callers requiring those semantics must construct the mode
explicitly with bitwise OR, and the kernel will apply OpenBSD's
nosuid mount-option and pledge restrictions to filter the effective
mode.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "openbsd_arm64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0o644 = rw-r--r-- (regular file default)
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0o755 = rwxr-xr-x (executable / directory default)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2)
measures relative to end-of-file. OpenBSD inherits the same values as
every POSIX kernel, defined in `sys/sys/unistd.h`. These match the
bare-name dispatcher's expectations and the `syscall_lseek` wrapper's
`whence` parameter.
Source: OpenBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` (#define SEEK_SET 0, SEEK_CUR 1,
SEEK_END 2); POSIX.1-2017 §unistd.h.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to this proc on openbsd_arm64
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1. Bodies
are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlinable at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek`
with these whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file
position against the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled
negative offset combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected position
prior to file start, which OpenBSD's lseek will reject with EINVAL
on conforming kernels. Devices and pipes do not support seeking;
lseek on those file descriptors returns -ESPIPE regardless of whence.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "openbsd_arm64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall convention:
Note: - X8 = syscall number
Note: - X0-X5 = arguments 1-6
Note: - Stack = arguments 7+
Note: - Return value in X0

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 0 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 1 argument
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load argument 1 into X0
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-24]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 2 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-2 into X0-X1
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-32]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 3 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-3 into X0-X2
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-40]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 4 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-4 into X0-X3
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]
        ldr x3, [fp, #-40]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-48]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "openbsd_arm64_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OpenBSD ARM64 syscall with 5 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-5 into X0-X4
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]
        ldr x3, [fp, #-40]
        ldr x4, [fp, #-48]

