Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (syscall_<name> bare form)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 10 `syscall_<name>` bare-name
procs (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close,
syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek). Each platform module must export the same names so the
dispatcher's bare-name routing can resolve to platform-correct ABI
behaviour. On OpenBSD ARM64 each wrapper routes through the correct
syscall_N generic dispatcher with the matching SYS_* number; the
generic dispatcher loads X8 with the syscall number, X0..X5 with
arguments, and issues `svc #0`.

These are NOT duplicates of the lower-section POSIX-style `read`/`write`/
`open`/... wrappers above: those use traditional POSIX short names for
backward compatibility with v0.0.7.5-era Runa standard library code;
the `syscall_<name>` forms below are what the platform-dispatch
infrastructure expects per the P2-B design's "Per-platform syscall
inventory" section. Both naming schemes coexist; callers select based
on whether they need the historical POSIX name or the dispatcher-aware
form.

Source for OpenBSD ARM64 syscall numbers: OpenBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h`
(numbers stable on the OpenBSD 7.x release series; arm64 inherits the
asm-generic ARM64 SVC trap convention, so the same syscall numbers
apply as on openbsd_x64 via the kernel's MD-independent syscall table).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper computes the syscall number via the matching SYS_* accessor
(itself a constant return on openbsd_arm64) and forwards arguments to
the `syscall_N` generic dispatcher matching the arity. The generic
dispatcher loads X8 with the syscall number and X0..X5 with arguments,
then issues `svc #0` and returns X0. Negative X0 values are OpenBSD-ABI
errno indications which the wrapper propagates unchanged to the caller.

Argument-passing convention (all values 64-bit on arm64):
- syscall_read(fd, buf, count) -> SYS_READ(3) via syscall_3
- syscall_write(fd, buf, count) -> SYS_WRITE(4) via syscall_3
- syscall_open(path, flags, mode) -> SYS_OPEN(5) via syscall_3
- syscall_close(fd) -> SYS_CLOSE(6) via syscall_1
- syscall_exit(status) -> SYS_EXIT(1) via syscall_1 (whole-process exit)
- syscall_brk(addr) -> SYS_BRK(17) via syscall_1 (routes to sys_obreak)
- syscall_mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset) -> SYS_MMAP(49) via syscall_6
- syscall_munmap(addr, len) -> SYS_MUNMAP(73) via syscall_2
- syscall_fstat(fd, statbuf) -> SYS_FSTAT(53) via syscall_2
- syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence) -> SYS_LSEEK(166) via syscall_3

Note on SYS_OPEN: OpenBSD retains the historical `open(2)` syscall (5)
alongside the newer `openat(2)` (287) — unlike linux_arm64 which has
only openat. Callers of syscall_open on openbsd_arm64 get the legacy
open path directly. For new code, prefer the openat-based path via
syscall_openat() (the dispatcher's higher-level openat wrapper) to
obtain unveil-aware relative-path resolution.

Note on SYS_LSEEK: returns 64-bit offset directly (no off64_t/llseek
distinction needed on a 64-bit ABI like arm64; the X0 register is 64
bits wide). The whence argument uses SEEK_SET/SEEK_CUR/SEEK_END
constants defined above.

Note on SYS_MMAP: OpenBSD's mmap entry (49) uses the modern 6-argument
form with byte-aligned offset (NOT page-aligned like Linux mmap2).
W^X enforcement: OpenBSD will reject `PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC` mappings
for non-static-binary callers; use PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE then mprotect
to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC after content write.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles down to: load constant syscall number, marshal
arguments through stack frame to X0..X5/X8, issue `svc #0`. Total cost
is dominated by the kernel-mode trap, not the wrapper's Runa-level
indirection. The wrapper itself adds 2-3 instructions of glue beyond
the generic syscall_N body. Do not introduce caching or memoisation;
syscalls are not pure functions and the kernel cost dominates.

For hot-path syscall sites (e.g. read/write in tight I/O loops), prefer
calling the generic `syscall_3` directly with the SYS_* constant
inlined, avoiding the intermediate wrapper. The wrapper exists for
dispatcher contract compliance, not as a recommended fast-path entry.

OpenBSD-specific: the kernel's syscall entry path performs `pledge`
and `unveil` enforcement; pledged programs see additional kernel-side
checks before the actual syscall body runs. For latency-sensitive
syscall loops on pledged programs, ensure the requested promise set
is the smallest set that satisfies the program's needs, which keeps
the kernel-side validation table compact.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments are passed verbatim to the
OpenBSD kernel. The wrapper performs no validation; the kernel enforces
all access controls (UID/GID, file mode, mount restrictions, pledge
promises, unveil paths). Callers must NOT use these wrappers to issue
syscalls on behalf of an untrusted source without `pledge()` /
`unveil()` confinement at the process level.

In particular:
- syscall_open: untrusted `path` strings traverse the filesystem
  subject only to DAC and unveil restrictions; sandboxed callers
  must establish an unveil path set before invoking, or rely on
  pledge("rpath wpath cpath") to limit reachable operations.
- syscall_mmap with PROT_EXEC: W^X violation; OpenBSD will reject
  PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC for dynamic content (the kernel enforces
  W^X by default and only static binaries / properly-signed code
  pages get a waiver). Callers requiring executable memory should
  mmap PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE first, write content, then mprotect to
  PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC.
- syscall_exit: terminates the entire process on OpenBSD (the kernel
  does whole-task teardown; OpenBSD has no per-thread exit syscall
  in the Linux sense — use SYS_THREXIT(302) for thread-only exit).
- syscall_brk on OpenBSD invokes sys_obreak (the legacy 4.3BSD heap-
  break path); modern OpenBSD libc uses mmap, not obreak. Avoid
  brk in new code.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in X0 for failure. The wrapper
returns this verbatim; positive values are syscall results (e.g. byte
counts, file descriptors, addresses). Caller MUST check sign of return
value before treating it as a syscall result. The OpenBSD ABI also
sets the CPSR carry flag on error (legacy mechanism); negative-return
check is the recommended portable test.
@End Security_Scope
